## Phase 2 — Database Deployment (Aiven MySQL)

The backend needs a cloud MySQL database before it can be deployed.

### Step 1 — Create a Free Aiven Account

1. Go to [https://aiven.io](https://aiven.io) → **Sign up** (free tier gives you one MySQL service).
2. Create a new **MySQL** service → choose the **Free** plan → pick the closest region to your users.
3. Wait for the service status to become **Running** (≈ 2–3 minutes).

### Step 2 — Get Your Connection Details

From the Aiven Console → your MySQL service → **Connection Information**, copy:

| Variable | Where to Find |
|---|---|
| `DB_HOST` | Host field (e.g. `mysql-xyz.aivencloud.com`) |
| `DB_USER` | User (usually `avnadmin`) |
| `DB_PASSWORD` | Password (click the eye icon) |
| `DB_NAME` | Default DB name (rename to `taskflow` in the console) |
| `DB_PORT` | Port (usually `27659` — **not 3306**) |
| `SSL_CA` | Download the CA Certificate file |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Aiven MySQL uses a **non-standard port** and requires an **SSL Certificate**. You must pass both in your backend connection config.

### Step 3 — Update Your Backend DB Connection

Open `d:\Developments\College Project\taskflow-backend\src\utils\db.js` (or wherever the pool is created) and ensure it supports SSL:

```js
const pool = mysql.createPool({
  host:     process.env.DB_HOST,
  port:     process.env.DB_PORT || 3306,
  user:     process.env.DB_USER,
  password: process.env.DB_PASSWORD,
  database: process.env.DB_NAME,
  ssl: { rejectUnauthorized: false },   // ← add this for Aiven
  waitForConnections: true,
  connectionLimit: 10,
});
```

### Step 4 — Run Migrations Against the Cloud Database

Temporarily add the cloud credentials to your local [.env](file:///d:/Developments/College%20Project/taskflow-backend/.env) (change them back after), then run:

```bash
cd "d:\Developments\College Project\taskflow-backend"
npm run migrate
npm run seed           # optional — only if you need seed data
```

Verify the tables exist by connecting with a MySQL client (TablePlus, DBeaver, or `mysql` CLI).

---

## Phase 3 — Backend Deployment (Render)

### Step 1 — Push Code to GitHub

If you haven't pushed yet:

```bash
cd "d:\Developments\College Project"
git add .
git commit -m "chore: prepare for production deployment"
git push origin main
```

> [!WARNING]
> Ensure [.env](file:///d:/Developments/College%20Project/taskflow-backend/.env) is **NOT** in the commit. Verify with `git status` before pushing.

### Step 2 — Create a Render Account & New Web Service

1. Go to [https://render.com](https://render.com) → **Sign Up** (use your GitHub account for easy integration).
2. Click **New +** → **Web Service**.
3. Connect your GitHub repository `Siddhantpal08/TaskFlow`.
4. Configure the service:

| Setting | Value |
|---|---|
| **Name** | `taskflow-backend` |
| **Root Directory** | `taskflow-backend` |
| **Runtime** | `Node` |
| **Build Command** | `npm install` |
| **Start Command** | `npm start` |
| **Plan** | Free |

### Step 3 — Set Environment Variables on Render

In your Render service → **Environment** tab → Add the following variables one by one:

```
PORT=10000                        ← Render assigns its own port; set this to 10000
NODE_ENV=production
DB_HOST=<your-aiven-host>
DB_PORT=<your-aiven-port>
DB_USER=<your-aiven-user>
DB_PASSWORD=<your-aiven-password>
DB_NAME=taskflow
JWT_SECRET=<a-long-random-string-min-32-chars>
JWT_REFRESH_SECRET=<another-long-random-string>
MAILTRAP_API_KEY=<your-mailtrap-token>
MAIL_FROM=hello@demomailtrap.com
CLIENT_URLS=https://taskflow-app.vercel.app,https://your-expo-tunnel-url
```

> [!NOTE]
> Generate strong secrets with: `node -e "console.log(require('crypto').randomBytes(64).toString('hex'))"`

### Step 4 — Deploy the Backend

1. Click **Deploy** (Render auto-builds from your GitHub repo).
2. Watch the build logs — it typically takes 2–4 minutes.
3. Once deployed, you'll get a URL like: `https://taskflow-backend.onrender.com`

### Step 5 — Verify Backend is Live

```bash
curl https://taskflow-backend.onrender.com/api/health
# OR open the URL in your browser
```

You should receive a `200 OK` JSON response. If you get a 503, check the Render logs.

> [!NOTE]
> **Render free tier sleeps after 15 minutes of inactivity.** The first request after a sleep takes ~30 seconds. This is normal for a college project demo — upgrade to the Starter plan ($7/month) for always-on behaviour.

---

## Phase 4 — Web Frontend Deployment (Vercel)

### Step 1 — Update the API Base URL

Before deploying the frontend, update the API URL to point to your live Render backend.

Find the file where you set the base API URL (likely `taskflow-app/src/api/` or a `.env` file) and update it:

Create `d:\Developments\College Project\taskflow-app\.env.production`:

```
VITE_API_URL=https://taskflow-backend.onrender.com/api
VITE_SOCKET_URL=https://taskflow-backend.onrender.com
```

Make sure your API calls use `import.meta.env.VITE_API_URL` as the base URL.  
Make sure your Socket.IO client uses `import.meta.env.VITE_SOCKET_URL`.

### Step 2 — Test the Production Build Locally

```bash
cd "d:\Developments\College Project\taskflow-app"
npm run build          # creates the /dist folder
npm run preview        # serves /dist locally — test this before deploying
```

Open `http://localhost:4173` and verify the app works with the Render backend.

### Step 3 — Create a Vercel Account & Deploy

1. Go to [https://vercel.com](https://vercel.com) → Sign Up with GitHub.
2. Click **Add New → Project** → import `Siddhantpal08/TaskFlow`.
3. Configure the project:

| Setting | Value |
|---|---|
| **Root Directory** | `taskflow-app` |
| **Framework Preset** | Vite |
| **Build Command** | `npm run build` |
| **Output Directory** | `dist` |

### Step 4 — Set Environment Variables on Vercel

In your Vercel project → **Settings → Environment Variables**, add:

```
VITE_API_URL=https://taskflow-backend.onrender.com/api
VITE_SOCKET_URL=https://taskflow-backend.onrender.com
```

### Step 5 — Deploy & Get Your URL

1. Click **Deploy**. Vercel builds and deploys in ~1 minute.
2. You'll receive a URL like: `https://taskflow-app.vercel.app`

### Step 6 — Update CORS on the Backend

Go back to Render → Environment Variables → update `CLIENT_URLS`:

```
CLIENT_URLS=https://taskflow-app.vercel.app
```

Then trigger a **Manual Deploy** on Render (so the new CORS config takes effect).

### Step 7 — Verify the Web App

1. Open `https://taskflow-app.vercel.app` in your browser.
2. Register a new account (confirm email OTP works via Mailtrap).
3. Log in → verify Dashboard loads tasks.
4. Open two browser tabs → verify real-time Socket.IO updates work (assign a task in one tab, see it appear in the other).

---

## Phase 5 — Mobile App Deployment (Expo)

The mobile app has two options: **Quick Share (Expo Go)** for demo purposes, or **Full Native Build (EAS)** for production APK/IPA.

### Option A — Quick Share via Expo Go (Recommended for College Demo)

This lets anyone with the **Expo Go** app scan a QR code and run your app instantly — no app store submission needed.

#### Step 1 — Update the API URL in Mobile App

Find where the mobile app defines its API base URL (likely `taskflow-mobile/src/api/` or `App.js`) and update it to the Render backend:

```js
const API_BASE = 'https://taskflow-backend.onrender.com/api';
const SOCKET_URL = 'https://taskflow-backend.onrender.com';
```

#### Step 2 — Publish to Expo

```bash
cd "d:\Developments\College Project\taskflow-mobile"
npm install
npx expo login          # log in with your Expo account (create one at expo.dev if needed)
npx expo publish        # publishes to Expo's CDN — creates a shareable link
```

> [!NOTE]
> After publishing, you'll get a URL like `exp://exp.host/@your-username/taskflow-mobile`.  
> Anyone can open this in **Expo Go** on Android or iOS.

#### Step 3 — Share the App

Copy the published URL from the terminal and share it. Recipients:
1. Install **Expo Go** from the Play Store / App Store.
2. Open Expo Go → **Enter URL manually** → paste the URL.

---

### Option B — Full Native APK Build (EAS Build)

For a real Android APK that can be installed directly on any phone (no Expo Go needed).

#### Step 1 — Install EAS CLI

```bash
npm install -g eas-cli
eas login              # log in with your Expo account
```

#### Step 2 — Configure EAS

```bash
cd "d:\Developments\College Project\taskflow-mobile"
eas build:configure    # creates eas.json automatically
```

#### Step 3 — Build the APK

```bash
eas build -p android --profile preview
```

This submits the build to Expo's cloud infrastructure. It takes 5–15 minutes. When done, you'll get a download link for the `.apk` file.

#### Step 4 — Install the APK

Download the APK → transfer to your Android phone → enable **Install from Unknown Sources** in settings → install.

---

## Phase 6 — Post-Deployment Verification

Run through this checklist after every component is deployed:

| Check | How to Verify |
|---|---|
| Backend health | `GET https://taskflow-backend.onrender.com/api/health` → 200 OK |
| User registration | Register a new account → receive OTP email via Mailtrap |
| Login & JWT | Log in → check that a JWT cookie/token is set |
| Task CRUD | Create, edit, delete a task → verify in the DB via Aiven console |
| Notifications | Assign a task to a user → verify they receive a notification |
| Real-time (Socket.IO) | Open two browser sessions → create a task in one → see it appear in the other live |
| Mobile connectivity | Log in on Expo Go → navigate all screens without API errors |
| CORS | Open browser DevTools → confirm no CORS errors in the Console |
| Rate limiting | Hit the API 100+ times rapidly → confirm you get `429 Too Many Requests` |

---

## Phase 7 — Troubleshooting Common Issues

### ❌ Backend 503 on Render

- **Cause**: Free tier is sleeping.
- **Fix**: Wait 30 seconds for the cold start, then retry. Or upgrade to Starter plan.

### ❌ CORS Error in Browser Console

- **Cause**: `CLIENT_URLS` on Render doesn't include your Vercel URL.
- **Fix**: Update `CLIENT_URLS` on Render → redeploy backend.

### ❌ DB Connection Refused / SSL Error

- **Cause**: Missing `ssl: { rejectUnauthorized: false }` in the pool config, or wrong Aiven port.
- **Fix**: Add the SSL option and double-check `DB_PORT` (Aiven uses a custom port, not 3306).

### ❌ Vite Build Error — `import.meta.env` is undefined

- **Cause**: Environment variables not set on Vercel, or they don't start with `VITE_`.
- **Fix**: All frontend env vars **must** start with `VITE_`. Re-add them on Vercel → redeploy.

### ❌ Socket.IO Not Connecting on Mobile

- **Cause**: Mobile app still pointing to `localhost` instead of the Render URL.
- **Fix**: Update `SOCKET_URL` in the mobile app source → republish with `npx expo publish`.

### ❌ JWT Token Invalid / 401 Unauthorized

- **Cause**: `JWT_SECRET` on Render is different from what was used to sign existing tokens.
- **Fix**: Make sure you set `JWT_SECRET` once and never change it. Users will need to log in again if it changes.

### ❌ Mailtrap Email Not Sending

- **Cause**: `MAILTRAP_API_KEY` is wrong or the `MAIL_FROM` domain is not verified.
- **Fix**: Copy the API key from Mailtrap → Sending Domains → verify `demomailtrap.com` is allowed.

---

## Summary — Deployment Order

```
1. ✅ Run all tests locally (npm test)
2. ✅ Deploy MySQL database to Aiven
3. ✅ Run migrations against Aiven DB
4. ✅ Push code to GitHub
5. ✅ Deploy backend to Render + set env vars
6. ✅ Verify backend is live (health check)
7. ✅ Update web frontend API URL env vars
8. ✅ Deploy frontend to Vercel
9. ✅ Update CORS on Render with Vercel URL
10. ✅ Update mobile app API URL → publish to Expo
11. ✅ Run full post-deployment verification checklist
```
